  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects include:\n\n1. In the United States:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Enforced by agencies like FinCEN\n\n2. Internationally:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards\n- European Union's AML Directives\n- Most countries have specific AML laws\n\n3. Common requirements:\n- Customer identification\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Reporting suspicious activities\n- Maintaining records\n- Implementing compliance programs\n\n4. Covered institutions:\n- Banks\n- Credit unions\n- Money transfer services\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n- Investment firms\n\nThese regulations aim to detect and prevent financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illegal financial activities.",
